  "text": "AddressSanitizer (ASan) is a memory safety tool implemented in both LLVM and GCC. In the LLVM project (llvm/llvm-project), the key implementation files are: (1) compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp contains the standard library function interceptors using the INTERCEPTOR macro pattern, which hooks malloc, strcpy, memcpy, and other libc functions to detect memory errors at runtime. (2) compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp implements the runtime initialization via the AsanInitInternal() function and AsanInitializer class, which set up shadow memory mapping and initialize the ASan runtime before program execution. (3) llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp contains the LLVM IR-level instrumentation pass with the main AddressSanitizer class that inserts memory access checks at the IR level, along with ModuleAddressSanitizer for module-level instrumentation and FunctionStackPoisoner for stack variable protection. In the GCC project (gcc-mirror/gcc), the implementation files are: (4) gcc/asan.cc contains the GCC ASan implementation with the pass_asan and pass_asan_O0 gimple optimization passes, and the asan_instrument() function that instruments memory operations with shadow memory checks. (5) gcc/asan.h provides the public API declarations and macro definitions including ASAN_SHADOW_SHIFT, red zone sizes, stack magic numbers, and function declarations for ASan runtime functionality. Both implementations follow the same algorithm: maintaining shadow memory to track the state of program memory, intercepting memory operations, and checking shadow values before memory accesses to detect use-after-free and out-of-bounds errors."
}

